han a game mechanism.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;There is very little content in the game that works the other way around. There are a total of two raid encounters in the entire game that are level restricted for younger players in any way.  There is only one zone... the tutorial zone... that you cannot enter if you are over a certain level.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;A great deal of this is driven by the player base itself rather than the designers or developers. Players adhere to the 'time == rewards' mechanism if anything, more firmly than the game developers. The most vocal players are more likely to adhere to it more than less vocal players. Accordingly, the game developers are made to understand that there is more demand for high level content than low- or mid-level content. They meet the demand with new content and reinforce this concept in a cyclical manner.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Again, this encourages some abuses, such as power-levelling and ebaying since there is very little reason to 'remain young' or replay the game with lower level characters for the sake of experiencing content.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;It also actively discourages new players from starting EQ since the investments to see substantial rewards are very well known and broadly advertised.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;- EQ is a very old game&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Six years is unheard of in the world of game design. Think of other games that are six years old. Most PC games released in 1999 were not 3d games, let alone multiplayer games. The only other 'massive' online game, Ultima Online, was 2D. The double handful of 3D games that did exist were only starting to rely on 3D graphics rendering technology.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Being so old, EQ has a lot of built-up crud, including old, difficult to maintain software, old, difficult to maintain hardware, and an old, difficult to please user base. Everquest is incredibly 'crufty' as it were. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;This has some bonuses and some negatives. The Everquest client is a surprisingly mature and robust piece of software with a modular architecture. It contains a wealth of features and relatively little bloat. Better than 99% of the EQ game client's disk-space requirements are used by data files-- the graphics, sounds, and models that make up the game world.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The older client software gets, however, the more difficult it is to maintain in the face of changing technology. EQ's major graphics engine has had to have major overhauls not once, but twice during its history, each overhaul bringing a tribulation of grief and suffering along for the ride.  EQ does not perform nearly as well as it could be expected to, simply because there is so much legacy code still in place.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;New games are often designed to target the cutting edge of PC technology in terms of requirements. EQ has always targeted this edge. This means that a 6 year old game often still runs with some painful caveats... such as amazingly poor performance when a 'busy' area is displayed. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;"Lag" used to refer to data loss due to poor network transmission. Now, to the majority of EQ players, it means a poor graphical frame-rate.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;This is not just a problem on the client side. EQ's game rules have changed dramatically over the years. Rather than a new set of rules for a new era, EQ players are still subject to modifications of rules that were crafted in 1999. Each sweeping rule change in response to a new technology or market demand has the potential to make EQ unplayable. Many redundant rule-sets and game mechanisms exist, often causing player confusion or strife. There are even multiple sound, model, and graphics formats used to store the game world, all of which must be maintained as if they were brand new.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;- EQ has unprecedented inertia&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Since EQ is such an old game and its rules are so old, a vocal portion of it's population has strong negative reactions to change that have been reinforced over six years. Any rule change, positive or negative, is met with hysteria and argument.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Game developers are in the unenviable position of having to vet their every action before players who may view it differently or violently oppose it. Players may object to attempts to lessen the learning curve associated with the game or view any changes to the difficulty as one part of the game as an attack against them.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Let's look at a completely hypothetical situation to understand this argument. Let's say, and this is completely for the sake of discussion and not a statement of suggestion, that SOE decided to make EQ an entirely raid-oriented game. All characters start the game able to raid and most of the game mechanics are altered so that the game's primary mechanic is large, multi-group raids.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Most reading can imagine the initial outcry over such a decision.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Although many people play EQ for raiding purposes alone, such a move would be violently protested. Even if it were to prove wildly successful, howls of disgust and anguish would rise. Messageboards would be engulfed in flames, brimstone, and sulfur. The sun was as black as satcloth and the moon was as red as blood. Yea verily.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Now let's take it the opposite direction. Let's assume that SOE decided t o make EQ an entirely single-group oriented game. All game mechanics are altered so that the game's primary mechanic is play with six or less people. Any attempt to engage a an encounter with more than 6 people is not rewarded.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The same apocalypse, trials, and tribulations, and end times would STILL result. There would still be rioting and war in the streets. Lions would still lie with lambs. Dogs and cats, living together. Total chaos.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;This inertia makes changes to the game EXTREMELY difficult, both for game developers, the management of SOE, and for inertial mass of players as well.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;These statements are not meant to try to provoke instantaneous, sweeping change in the game. They're meant to be a perspective that will help others, hopefully the game developers as well, understand problems with the game and think of ways to alleviate them.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;My own break from EQ will probably not be too long. Maybe when I come back, some of these  problems will have evaporated.</description>
