    <item>
      <title>Re: Thoughts of a... resting... EQ player</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&amp;message.id=84151#M84151</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;One of the few turn-offs of EQ1 at the moment is the extremely long downtime you are subjected to after recovering from a wipe (group or raid situation).&amp;nbsp; After doing the corpse run, your group/raid ends up having to rebuff and then med up to full.&amp;nbsp; All of this can take anywhere from 30 minutes up to an hour, depending on the encounter.&amp;nbsp; On a particularly nasty encounter, it takes a hardcore devoted player to sit through several wipes and long recovery times each time.&amp;nbsp; This is one of the big sources of burnout associated with EQ1.&amp;nbsp; The problem gets worse the higher into content you get (when casters get &amp;gt;10k mana pools, etc.).&amp;nbsp; It would be nice if there was higher out-of-combat-only regeneration that lowered these recovery times.&amp;nbsp; If such regen&amp;nbsp;suspended in combat situations, it wouldn't trivialize much.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The problem with that would&amp;nbsp;be somehow&amp;nbsp;easily&amp;nbsp;implementing "states" (i.e. like&amp;nbsp;encounter locking in EQ2).&amp;nbsp; That in itself would be a mammoth project programming wise.&amp;nbsp; I don't want EQ1 to be EQ2 or WoW, but there is a certain draw to being able to quickly recover from a failure and get back in the saddle again.&amp;nbsp; I don't think examining such possibilities in EQ1 would "dumb down" the game too much if handled gracefully.&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
